@node not28 "FUBAR DEVELOPMENT NEWS"
                             FUBAR DEVELOPMENT NEWS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

From: "bartman" <bartman@rosande.nu>

A long, long delay in e-mail once again, but be assured it's only for the good.
People want to know precisely what's been going on in regards to FUBAR's
development, so here it is.

Recently, I have been putting every effort into development, working 12 hours a
day on average, and this will continue until it's completely finished (what a
life).

But just where is development? What about this beta I promised two weeks ago?
Well, oops is all I can say to that. I'm very sure now that you lot all will
take what I say with a pinch of salt when it comes to dates, since I evidently
make a huge cock-up. Before I answer the beta question, here's what's been going
on precisely.

Since the demise of FUDGE (good idea, just not practical) the engine had to go
through several large changes to get it back to speed, after removing the FUDGE
code. Although, all the changes were for the good: improved refresh times,
improved sound support and quicker responses to the user. The video sub-system
runs just 5 frames slower when used with AGA compared to a graphics card - but
of course, it's much smoother on a graphics card. The sound sub-system is
complete panoramic 16-bit stereo (providing the user has the hardware which erm,
I don't) and supports streamed music files (i.e. sampled CDDA played from hard
disk). And who can forget the network sub-system, the input sub-system and
others.

Of course, when FUDGE was killed off, there wasn't much in the way of something
to play - it's all very well having a fancy driving system, but if there's
nothing to drive there's no point. Well, the finger was removed from the
metaphorical arse and lo and behold a quot;gamequot; directory appeared in the
FUBAR_Src dir on my hard disk.

Since FUBAR is a single-player and multiplayer game it has to be made like a
multiplayer game, and quot;hackquot; single-player support into it. How do you
make a multiplayer game? Well, since this is e-mail, you'll be aware of what a
quot;serverquot; is and what a quot;clientquot; is. FUBAR has to be both of
those things at the same time.

The quot;FUBAR serverquot; is responsible for actually running the game and
simulation. It must be around otherwise there can't be a game. The quot;FUBAR
clientquot; allows the player/user (or quot;clientquot;) to control what he/she
wants to do and communicate their objectives to the server. That's the basics,
and that's what it does.

The server handles all the simulation and orgastration which is required to make
the game work. This simulation includes building troops consisting of units,
creating cities in the world and building buildings inside cities to make them
of any use. The simulation also handles stuff the player can't necessarily
control - nature... weather effects and time, spring to mind.

The client translates all the server information into something the player will
(hopefully) understand on their screen. Things like, drawing the World Map,
displaying cities, giving the player feedback on goings on, etc.. That's the
specifics.

And, the specifics also mean reality. Yes, that's right. Re-al-it-y. This is
pretty much exactly what the game (yes, the GAME) does at this present moment in
time. So, to recap:

   * Full server support, via local connection (i.e. single player) or remote
     connection (via Internet/LAN/TCP stack).
   * Complete world support, featuring seasoned weather effects.
   * City creation and building. Relevant building simulation also supported,
     including unit training, resource mining, and other stuff.
   * Troop creation and deployment.

And also...

   * Full user-controlled front end, with logos, buttons and interactive system
     configuration (should the user want to change the pretty accurate default
     settings, tuned to their system).
   * Streamed music, played from hard disk (in 16-bit, hardware permitting) or
     played from CD tracks (heh, supported and works, but erm, I can't burn the
     real CD tracks since I don't have a CD-R :)
   * Complete World Map editor, with square assignment, and mission settings.

Plus a whole bunch of crap, which wouldn't interest the most computer-literate
people in the world.

So there you have it. Now, to answer that question - where's the beta? Here's my
plan for this:

Since Amiga Active are wondering what's going on, I think I'll get a demo ready
first, before I release a beta. There are plenty of little tweeks and suprises I
have to add before I can really call it a game, and I'd like to reserve those
for the beta, as the game as it stands is pretty cool enough for a simple demo.
Probably release a more complex demo when the beta has been released and tested.
That's my plan.

There's still one or two glitches in the simulation at the moment which can
detract from playability, which is why I am neglecting to release the demo now.
However, by Sunday (Monday at the latest) this will all be fixed, and the demo
shall be ready for release. Never thought I'd hear myself type that (grin :).

quot;This is all well and good, but what about the battle screen?quot; This is a
good question. I am pretty angry about the lack of input from most sources, and
I have realised in the past weeks that I am writing this whole game myself. Bare
in mind that I am doing the work of six people, and I'm loving every minute of
it (hey look, a pink elephant).

So the fate of the battle screen rests in the hands of artists. See, the problem
is that the battle screen is 99% visual. It's indiviual units moving around the
screen, animated in real-time on a tiled animated background. Note the key words
there: quot;movingquot;, quot;animatedquot;, quot;real-timequot;. All require
someone who can draw. Don't look at me, for Hell's sake.

If this lack of graphics (that means rendered animations for all the units -
designs that I do have (yes Ross, I found them! :)) isn't resolved quickly it
looks like goodbye to the battle screen. Which is a huge shame since there is so
many things we can do with it, from a multiplayer point of view - Capture The
Flag, Skirmish, Troop Deployment (heh, that's cool)... but, all of it requires
some cool graphics, which I most certianly aren't capable of doing. Shame.

Thankfully to address the lack-of-graphics problem for the World Map, I've got
the knack of drawing realistic-looking maps in Paint Shop Pro - sure, I draw in
24-bit, but drawing in 256 colours is an art in itself...

Graphics problems have dogged the project since day one. And it's come too far
now to stop, so solutions are required, if there are any. I'd be happy to leave
the game as a simulation, but the real-time element is unique - it's something I
don't want to hold off until we do the PC version... providing we can find the
manpower.

But anyway, I digress. With a quot;code preview demoquot; due at the weekend,
that's something to look forward to, eh?
