@node not41 "HOME ELECTRONICS WORLD '99 REPORT BY CAGHAN DEMIRCI"
               HOME ELECTRONICS WORLD '99 REPORT BY CAGHAN DEMIRCI
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE

Home Electronics World '99 Report by Caghan Demirci
(Edited by James Russell, AO Editor-in-Chief at large)

1999-10-21 - (Amiga.org) - From the desk of Amiga.org's roving reporter, Caghan
Demirci, comes this recount of the recent Home Electronics World (HEW) show in
Cologne, Germany.

I rushed into the Home Electronics World 99 at noon on Saturday November 13th,
only to find my vision blocked by a barrage of irrelevant "home electronics"
stands, who would gladly sell you their PC hardware and software ranging from
the odd SCSI cable to the slick steering wheel at bargain prices. The Amiga
stands gathered together at the further end of the hall, with no clear
separation between the two partitions.

In the very middle of the floor towered the Amiga Inc. stand in all its
grandeur, looming over the crowd and the various Amiga dealers on its four
sides. The stand included a little bar where you could eat sausages, drink coke,
and, well, eat sausages and sit around chatting. A constant hubbub was afoot
right outside at the very center of Amiga Inc.'s facade. All kinds of novelty
items were up for grabs, with Amiga posters, pens, matchboxes, cups, cola,
stickers, and even Amiga socks and boxer shorts, (and stop with the boing balls
jokes!). Two of the walls led to offices and little depots, and through the
other two you could enter and leave. This whole cube was surrounded by showcases
and stood facing outwards, and further toward the rim there are many display
"nodes" suggesting a bigger rectangle. The stand was so dominant that even if
you thought you were walking in the same direction, you would soon end up back
at some unexpected node of the central stand.

The highlight of Amiga Inc.'s stand this year was the Amiga history exhibition
with showcases on three sides of the central cube. Displayed items ranged from
an ancient Commodore PC to the wedge box and desktop Amigas, "Best computer of
the year" awards, the CDTV, the CD32 and finally the Walker. If you browsed
carefully, you couldn't help but stumble upon the A500 PPC card by DCE that
never actually got released. "Is that even possible?" you ask. An adapter kludge
to bring the BlizzardPPC and the A500 motherboard together, and you have it. Try
running Wipeout on that!

One of the nodes was dedicated to ongoing IRC conferences at #hew99. Have you
ever wondered who the guy was that told you "Send me a '?' and I'll put you on
the question queue?" For the first time in my life, I've seen the administrator
for real. This guy has to sit in front of his computer all day typing his time
away, -- did you know he ate his breakfast, lunch and supper in front of the
monitor as well?

At a second Amiga Internet node anyone could try his hand out at the new Voyager
3.0.37, or AmTelnet, and more. Right beside this node was the AmigaOS 3.5
demonstration stand, receiving continuous attention from a host of people who
seriously considered leaving the fair with this wonder box under their arms,
also for sale at the Amiga Inc. stand. One couldn't help noticing that the
stand employee was constantly very busy displaying the secrets of the updated
OS and advocating its future prospects. The very curious onlookers selected
multiple icons and dragged them over the screen, exclaiming "Echt cool!" when
they beheld the neat dragging effect.

Another node was Amiga Zentrum Thuringen showing off TVPaint, and what drew
particular attention there was Amiga LinuxPPC running on various and sundry
Amiga screens. APUS is one of Amiga's really tight grips on survival, and the
fact that LinuxPPC was being exhibited on almost the same level with OS 3.5
shows how much significance Amiga Inc. grants to it. KDE ran superbly,
multitasking rather well with an X11amp for good company, and on one other
screen AfterStep was running its super-fast rounds around the PowerPC CPU.

When he wasn't rushing to his office or to the bathroom for a quick break, Amiga
vice president Petro Tyschtschenko could always be seen surrounded by Amigans
from around Europe. As this is my first Amiga fair, (gulp!) I gathered up the
courage and finally went up and met him. I must say Amiga's vice president is a
really, really nice man; the community is lucky to be headed by someone who
loves and cares about the Amiga as much as Petro does. No one else from Amiga
Inc. came along -- probably they believed rightly that they would be scorned and
absorbed in arguments without end. "I have to sell stuff and keep a business
running," says Petro. "Business as usual." Some say he wasn't as cheerful as in
the previous fairs; but as to how much of the shaken and insecure mood of his
listeners infected him, no one can know. Supposedly the Amiga section of the
show is smaller than in the previous years, and the aisles have been widened to
make strolling easier; even so, there were crowds at every stand, talking,
arguing, and shopping.

Haage&Partner

Haage&Partner, now of OS 3.5 fame, was the star of the show. They had a big, big
stand, in fact the whole block with its four sides. Jurgen Haage was bustling
about trying to make money and talking with curious chaps about the Amiga market
situation. One couldn't help noticing that on Saturday, the AmigaOS 3.5 boxes at
his stand were almost sold out!

Gone (at last!) from Amiga stands are the faint OS 3.1 screens in low resolution
that once embarrassed Amigans in front of PC-owning visitors. In practically
every stand, OS 3.5 was installed and in full color, high resolution. The
popular OS was selling in large quantities at the fair, true, but Haage&Partner
need to sell more. Jurgen Haage was rightly concerned about piracy. He explained
that Haage&Partner had spent so much development effort on OS 3.5, and
maintained such a cheap price tag for an operating system, that the availability
of pirate copies was destructive and hostile.

Jurgen Haage agreed that the untimely launch of the AmigaOS open source petition
had put a lot of impulse OS 3.5 buyers off the cause. After a few months of the
OS release, the campaign could have done no harm, but when it got launched right
before the release, many people could have convinced themselves that
Haage&Partner shouldn't have done in-house OS development in the first place!
Nonetheless, Jurgen Haage believes that AmigaOS can eventually go open source,
but not in the way petitioners suggest. When patent problems are out of the way,
open source development should be a strictly centralized and thoroughly guided
effort, much like Netscape's Mozilla project, where everyone who is given access
to the source must describe exactly what he has done with it and turn it in.
Petro, too, is not very interested in what the open source campaign can do. "My
first priority now is to convert the OS to the PowerPC," he says.

At any rate, Jurgen Haage is seriously determined to produce OS 3.6 (where Miami
might be replaced with Genesis because of financial problems).

One booth at the show sported a tower containing an IBM PowerPC motherboard.
Publication of the IBM PPC board specification to form a basis for the common
PPC platform (remember PReP?) obviously caused an excited stir among eminent
Amiga developers, since not only did it mean liberation from the CHRP swamp that
had suffocated the PPC, but it also implied that a PPC-based Amiga-compatible
motherboard could be produced with relative ease! That's right, an excellent
scheme that had been proposed several years ago but never realized -- an Amiga
motherboard running on the PowerPC chip -- is now at the very focus of Amiga
Inc.'s plans! Of course, the operating system will have to be converted to the
new CPU, a painful project that Haage&Partner is willing to undertake.

The other three sides of the stand were taken up by promotions for a lot of fine
software, with several computers running demos. On display were titles such as
the Amiga Developers' CD, Fusion, Genesis, NetConnect (version 3, apparently),
STFax, Pagestream, AmigaWriter, StormC, ImageFX, Tornado3D, Warp3D, StormMesa,
and a recurring demo of Wipeout. FusionPPC is supposedly due out on the 20th of
November. Although non-AmigaOS excitement is now primarily channeled into
LinuxPPC, Fusion could definitely stir up some thrill into those poised to brag
about their Office 98 or VirtualPC or Connectix Virtual Game Station they will
run on their MacOS. Had FusionPPC launched a year or two ago, Amiga could be at
a different place. Same with OS 3.5.

Epic

Epic are converting Simon the Sorcerer 2, a graphical adventure game that was
planned to be released on the Amiga and the CD32 but never saw light of day, to
the Amiga. After perhaps an eternal time of uncertainty and speculation, one
could actually inspect a solidly running version of Simon 2. Considering that
the developer had to code the game from scratch, perhaps by reverse-engineering
the PC version, a lot of steady work has already gone into Amiga Simon 2.
Supposedly, when Epic can get the 500 preorders they need, development will get
a green light and "the author can finish the game by the end of January." For a
game like this, the more modest its system requirements are, the more it will
sel".

Apart from Simon 2, Epic had a fine stand overall, with a large collection of
old games. They also boasted newer software such as MakeCD and Foundation:
Director's Cut, but I really can't make a merry estimation of how much the
latter has sold. A running demo of the new Foundation really wouldn't do any
harm to dispel the prejudice many people harbour against the original
Foundation.

APC&TPC

The APC&TPC stand had some excitement in store. Amiga card game and the numerous
game and scene CD's they had for sale aside, the Phoenix demonstration by the
game's author was amassing groups of people around the clock. The jaw-dropping
demo was running on a BlizzardPPC with a BlizzardVisionPPC chucked in for good
measure, while the code utilized WarpOS and naturally Warp3D to access the 3D
functions of Permedia 2. As if a peak framerate of 70 and a sustainable frame
rate of 60 (which never dropped below 40 fps) weren't enough, you could hoist
the resolution up to 800 x 600 and Phoenix would still run with a peak rate of
65 and a sustainable rate of 40 (never dropping below 35 fps). Real-time enough
for ya? This game definitely got a few Lambda fans converted to Phoenix.

If you haven't seen it, you probably will not believe my description of the
engine. Slam the resolution up to a smooth-scrolling 640 x 480. Fly dangerously
close to tremendous space bases, run rounds around alien spaceships, try your
nervous finger at the trigger, and not a hint of slowdown. The 3D objects, and
space itself, are very colourful, debris pixels whizz insanely by as you
confide in your turbo boost, and you even get rewarded by a lens flare if you
manage the right angle.

Markus Pollmann, the author of Phoenix's engine, is not your everyday gamer who
plays Colony Wars all day on his Playstation and finally says, "Hey why don't we
chalk up something like that for the Amiga?" Contrary to public opinion, he has
been "constantly working on the game till now," and when asked about how one
could find all these algorithms to bring Phoenix souped up to the level of
modern space simulations, his matter-of-fact reply was "You invent them." Unlike
many other games developers who haven't yet seen the light, Markus's game is
programmed in a very clean C++, with which he can "implement the graphical
functions more easily."

As it had already been announced, there will not be Frontier-style trade in the
game, however we will definitely see a host of alien races with an enticing
story to match. Missions are not there yet, but a language for implementing
them is already in place, according to Pollmann. In the completed game you'll
be able to communicate with motherships, destroy space bases and wreak lots of
other havoc. As to how much there is to its completion, collision detection is
already "working very well," although it was shut down for the demo, and enemy
AI is "Okay, but will be better." Beautiful game. For me, the market seems
terribly hungry for a game of this nature; you don't even need to perfect it to
sell a good heap. So go and get Starfighter while you wait for this.

One weird stand had a real Atari SM124 on display, with its back-to-basics OS
smiling from a black-and-white screen.

HEW at large

The Schatztruhe stand was grand enough with its various showcases to draw the
public, and offered a great deal of the most modern Amiga software: Wipeout
2097, DOpus Magellan II, PFS3, Photogenics, Superview, versions of Miami, Amiga
Forever, and the Amiga Unix Compendium. Receiving perhaps more attention than
the DOpus T-Shirts and other novelty items was Urban Mueller advocating his
Aminet CD's and CD-sets. One keeps wondering when an Aminet CD that contains
solely PowerPC software will be able to come forth.

Buhler Electronic, who look as if they've been in the Amiga business since the
beginning of time and are now living their years of nostalgic retirement, were
calmly selling all sorts of peripherals like mice, cables, adapters, accelerator
cards, and even an authentic Commodore 570 CD interface! Hey, GVP530 anyone?

CoolBits constantly had a demo of Wipeout running. If Eat the Whistle hadn't
intervened, Wipeout would be hailed as the first commercial PowerPC game, but
nevertheless, it is always a wonder to behold a 100 percent finished game on a
BlizzardPPC. This race moves fast! Even though Wipeout is not the sort of game
that makes a lot of noise, there was always a small commotion before the
display. Since Clickboom wasn't around, T-Zero was silently for sale on the
shelves of CoolBits, along with VirtualGP, Starfighter, and several more that
could be seen at almost every stand.

Titan Computer's stand emphasized the upcoming Heretic II, running full screen
in 320x200, and surprising Amiga and PC users alike. Heretic II seems to run
perfectly on a BlizzardPPC/233 with a BlizzardVisionPPC. Because "it does not
yet utilize the 3D acceleration," (Warp3D anyone?) it tends to jump frames in
the more complicated scenes. In any case, old Cybervision64 and PicassoIV owners
are not out in the cold just yet. Although the code needs refining, Heretic II
is almost real!

Preordering forms were plenty, not only for Heretic II, but for Evil's Doom SE,
for which insatiable FRP dudes have been drooling for some time now, and Shogo
as well. Other than the good old Amiga CDs on the shelves, some digital effects
products like "Candy Effects for Casablanca" were up for grabs.

RBM Digitaltechnik would gladly sell you useful stuff like an IOBlix, a
ScanExpress, and the like.

The bipartite Albrecht Computer Technik (ACT) stand and the range of hardware
they had to offer was impressive. Some very handy Amiga gadgets were on sale,
such as Zorro boards, Cybervisions, IDEfix interfaces and the new PC mouse
adapter. Even though 060/50 board prices still roamed high, ACT were offering
their Apollo 040 boards for a steal. Get these boards while you can!

Individual Computers, who happily sold innovations like Silver Surfer,
Catweasel, and a new X-Surf for Zorro, occupied a modest stand. Advertised here
was an interesting new product called PPC680x0, which could "convert Amiga
assembler-source-codes straight to PowerPC source-codes."

DCE and KATO Development had also taken their stand with their Twister 1200 and
Melody 1200 Pro banging the speakers out of shape. With the help of a Winamp
clone called AMPlifier, the boards sounded remarkably good.

Eyetech Group Ltd. had what I take to be a Scala MM400 machine with multimedia
stuff on display. EASys, a new Workbench replacement "designed to make using
Workbench easier," said a representative.

Annex, now down to three people, danced twice during the day on a small stage
close to the entrance, enjoying keen attention from many attendants. In
addition to "Keep the Momentum Going," they also danced to the German premiere
of "The Spirit," quite an improvement on the former song.

Neil Bothwick is apparently working for both AmigaActive and Amiga Format "It's
not at all easy to get the magazine on the shelves," he replied when reproached
for the absence of AmigaActive in the rest of the world. "Mostly it is
impossible to distribute the magazine unless newsstands from that country
request it. And how can someone request it, if they don't even know about it?"

The AmigaPlus stand offered both developers' CD's and the German magazine
itself, with an 880KB floppy packed to the brim.

Also catching the surprised eye of many an attentive visitor were the three
wackos strolling around with their Iwin T-Shirts that shouted "Rotten tomatoes
here!" Apparently the community has become rather irritable after the chain of
recent disappointments and broken promises.

Perhaps the most poignant moment of the whole fair was when an Amiga stand
employee with a flaming red face and moist eyes said, "I've sworn, SWORN, that
if I win the lottery, I will sponsor the development of the new Amiga computer
architecture."

