@node not27 "WIPEOUT 2097 TROUBLESHOOTING"
                          WIPEOUT 2097 TROUBLESHOOTING
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Now, as Wipeout2097 has been released, it's time to release some trouble
shooting information as well. We expected all the time, that it will be a tricky
thing to make the game working, just like making any Warp3D application working,
because it depends on so many external factors. The game itself does most often
not cause the problems itself, but an inproper configuration of those external
components often cause many more problems.

I would appreciate, if this newsletter is spread, so that people will be able to
resolve their problems as soon as possible.

First of all, there is a support email address mentioned in the WO docs. People
having problems should mail to this address, it's directly linked to the
developers email address (so I will get them and will reply usually in the same
day). Up to now we were able to solve most problems. Note, that I won't continue
a discussion in the NG's, so anyone wanting to reply, please use private mail
(preferably sam_jordan@spin.ch).

In the documentation there is also a trouble shooting chapter which might solve
some problems.

If some of the serious problems get solved, then a patch will be released.

Known problems:

   * Accidentally we forgot to bump the version number of a library inside the
     Warp3D archive on CD (only production release), which can lead to heavy
     problems. To avoid problems, first *delete* the file
     libs:Warp3DPPC.library and afterwards install the Warp3D archive on CD.
     Besides that, if you already had W3DV2 installed, then you don't need the
     new archive. The new archive does only do two things:
      * provides a chroma test feature, which helps in displaying transparency
        correctly
      * fixes a problem when resizing the window

   * Second major problem: quite often, standard versions of CyberGfx aren't
     enough to play the game reliable, this is also valid for other Warp3D
     applications.

     Users with CV3D (yes, we got a lot of reports from satisfied Virge users)
     should either use Picasso96 or CyberGraphx4, as CGFX3/CV3D is almost
     completely unsuitable for 3d acceleration, because it doesn't support the
     bitmapcache feature.

     CVPPC/BVPPC: CGFX3 users should definitely download the *latest*
     cgxsystem.library and monitor driver from ftp.phase5.de, IIRC only these
     files don't have any problems at all (might also solve the 'not enough
     video memory' problem). CGFX4 users should make sure to have at least a
     monitor driver 4.0 beta 4 installed.

     Furthermore CGFX must be configured correctly. Dragging must be disabled
     and the bitmapcache feature must be enabled, otherwise no Warp3D
     application can work. All messages of the kind 'not enough video memory',
     'failed to open screen/window', 'failed to allocate bitmap' are definitely
     problems arising due to CyberGfx configuration problems.

   * Very important: make sure to *not* have a very large/very deep workbench
     and many window open when starting the game, otherwise the game won't have
     enough video memory and will reload the textures during the game. The game
     will then run at a few fps, and will display corrupt textures. A black
     screen, where 3d objects should be displayed, might also indicate a video
     memory shortage problem. As an example: I usually start the game with a
     1024*768*16 workbench, with not more than 1-2 not too large windows open,
     this is enough to run the game with triple buffering and max. texture
     memory set (certainly only for 8MB boards).

   * Then there is a powerpc.library in the Warp3D archive on the production CD.
     *Don't* touch it, it should have been removed, it's a quite old library.

     If you already had WarpUp 4 installed, then you shouldn't touch the WarpUp
     archive on CD either (it's the same). You might accenditally change some
     configuration variables, which could lead to problems.

   * There is another problem with the game concerning memory consumption.
     Although the game itself can be configured to eat less than 20MB
     (exclusive WarpUp memory consumption), it turned out that for a lot of
     people with even 32MB there were stability problems (the exact reason is
     unknown yet), so I definitely wouldn't recommend to buy the game when only
     24MB are present. 32MB users should make sure to reduce the 'texture memory
     slider' to a small value, because this doesn't only save video memory, but
     also fast memory. Additionally use double buffering instead of triple
     buffering if memory shortage might be expected (or try window mode).

     Of course, buying more RAM is another suitable solution. That's even more
     important, as it seems as some of the upcoming 3d games will even require
     64MB of RAM. This way stability problems of WO2097 could also be resolved.

   * If you get graphics errors (smearing, flashing), then you have most likely
     some patches/hacks installed, remove them. Other potential sources of such
     effects are too old CGFX files.

   * CD audio: right now we know, that for some IDE drives CD audio doesn't
     work. We currently don't know of any reliable possibility to play audio
     CD's, but the problem is investigated. If anyone has a good pointer to
     reliable audio CD playing functions we might integrate them and release a
     patch.

   * Performance: if you feel that the game doesn't run as fast as you would
     like it to run, then you can adjust some settings, mainly:
      * reduce view distance (F3)
      * enable fogging, reducing overdraw (F6)
      * disable filtering (F7)
      * reduce resolution

     Here some notes concerning WO2097 AMIGA efficiency: a lot of work was spent
     to accelerate the game as much as possible, and we can finally say that the
     efficiency is definitely better than the one of the PC version. The main
     slowdown reasons for now are on the one side the quite low fill rate of
     the Permedia2 and on the other side the slow bus systems (compared to
     other architectures). That's important because WO2097 has a really high
     polygon count, and every single vertex (point) of a polygon needs 30-40
     bytes to be transferred to the chip. More reasons are a lack of L2 cache
     (as the game deals with big memory areas internally), frequent cache
     flushes due to context switches and the context switches themselves, which
     take up a few milliseconds. So we had to compensate all these bottlenecks
     and I would say that we were successful in doing that. A plain port would
     have resulted in a very disappointing performance, that's for sure.

Hopefully we will see future OS versions, which will integrate all these new
technologies in a proper way, so that all this mess can be avoided. The goal
should be, that a game is installed and then simply works. I'm afraid that this
is impossible today, when talking about high-end games. But please, have
patience, consult the support (blame those people writing bad reports without
having contacted the support/developers first and which don't have any clue what
it means to develop high-end games for *AMIGA*), ask other people, and finally
you will manage to solve the problems, because other people also did it. And if
you once have a working system, then other similar games (like those coming from
Hyperion software) should work then without problems.

So all people have a lot of fun!

bye

